The paper discusses security vulnerabilities in online services, specifically Dropbox, and proposes an implementation of Path Oblivious RAM (Path ORAM) to obfuscate path access information. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses optimizations to the implementation of Path ORAM, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DB (Databases) sub-categories. The paper also discusses multi-client use, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the vulnerability of personal data, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.CY (Computers and Society) sub-category.
